{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":243730,"duration_api_ms":99238,"ttft_ms":2603,"ttft_stream_ms":2592,"time_to_request_ms":467,"num_turns":16,"result":"Done. All requirements are met.\n\n## What was wrong\nThe RabbitMQ side was already correct — the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin was enabled and metrics were being served on port `15692` at `/metrics` on all 3 pods. The problem was purely on the Prometheus side: its `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only scraped Prometheus itself (`localhost:9090`) and had no RabbitMQ scrape job.\n\n## Fix (native K8s resources only — no CRD/Operator/controller)\nEdited the existing `prometheus-config` ConfigMap and restarted the Prometheus Deployment:\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** using `static_configs` pointing at the 3 stable pod DNS names via the existing headless service:\n   - `rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rabbitmq.rules.yml`) defining `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`. Note: `rabbitmq_up` is *not* a native metric of the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin (it ships with a disallowed third-party exporter), so I synthesized it natively from Prometheus's own `up` series per the no-third-party constraint.\n\n## Verification\n- ✅ Metrics exposed on `15692` `/metrics` on all 3 pods.\n- ✅ 3 RabbitMQ targets show `health: up`.\n- ✅ `query=rabbitmq_up` returns **3 samples** (one per pod, all value `1`).\n- ✅ RabbitMQ unchanged and healthy — 3 pods `Running` (no restarts; I only touched Prometheus).","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"a0cdd91b-d507-4431-a635-ea6a3e361daa","total_cost_usd":0.690109,"usage":{"input_tokens":2763,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23931,"cache_read_input_tokens":517412,"output_tokens":7089,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23931,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_